[I do not know whether the numbers are correct but they are not difficult for
me to believe. Given that there are four distinct dengue viruses (dengue-1,
dengue-2, dengue-3, and dengue-4, and that cross-protection against the
others is not conferred by infection with any one, multiple
infections can and do occur. This is the principle problem with regard to
dengue hemorrhagic fever/dengue shock syndrome, i.e., sequential infections
leading to unique and increasing pathogenicity. For example, using the
numbers above, again which I do not know to be correct, 2 million cases/10
years = 200,000/year but if there are four types circulating (very doubtful
or we might have heard), that would make for 50,000 cases/12 million
inhabitants, 5 cases/1200 residents. Possible, but very unlikely. Does
anyone have data other than from a newspaper? Both CDC and Cuban
investigators were involved in studies of dengue in Ecuador a few years
ago. Thanks to the sharp eyes of Abramo for finding this. -- Mod CHC]
